					<head>Commentary</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85013597" rend="visible">
						<summary>A Judeo-Arabic commentary on the Hafṭarot of Numbers.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he" otherLangs="jrb">Hebrew, Judeo-Arabic</textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85013597">
							<locus from="2r" to="130v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Perush ῾al hafṭarot </title>
							<title xml:lang="he">פרוש על הפטרות </title>
							<note>
								<p>The pointed and partly accentuated Hebrew biblical text is embodied. The punctuation differs in parts from the standard masoretic recension.</p>
								<p>The commentary is anonymous, but from the information on folio 4r and 6v it can be inferred that he lived in Egypt. Cf <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">247</ref>.</p>
								<p>The works quotes several authorities, including Targum Jonathan, Rashi, Abu’l Walid and Abraham ibn Ezra.</p>
							</note>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="2r" to="22v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Hosea 2:1-22</title>
								<note>
									<p>Fragments of Ezekiel 44:20-21 begin on folio 1r.</p>
								</note>
							</msItem>
